Clean code is in a very weird spot as a rare. It only does one thing, and it doesn't do it very well. You must play clean code BEFORE playing any cards with compile errors, which is probably why it upgrades to be innate. Now, if your deck has two null pointers, a break, and philosophize, that might be worth it, but it becomes a bit of a chicken and the egg problem. You're probably not taking all those compile errors if you don't already have clean code, and you're probably not taking clean code unless you already have lots of compile error cards. This is made even more awkward by the presence of overheat at common, which is a pretty solid front-loaded damage card for act 1 on top of having error negation, which gives it much more flexibility, and makes it easier to take cards like null pointer alongside it. But, if your deck already has an overheat, than you probably aren't going to get full value out of clean codes 3 error negations, and there are almost certainly better rares you could be taking at the boss reward. Dev tools has a similar situation, where it provides the utility of error negation, but also is way more flexible than clean code. 

This really just leaves no room for clean code to compete, the card is very unappealing next to these other options, and compile errors in general just aren't prominent or dangerous enough to need this effect. The upgrade is nice in theory if you are putting tons of errors in your deck, but it's very unusual to end up in that position, and a simple energy discount would likely be better overall. I think a complete redesign is probably in order here, clean code just doesn't make any sense with the current amount/effect of errors, and is totally overshadowed by dev tools and overheat because of its lack of utility.
